TY  - JOUR
T1  - Sensitivity Analysis of Efficiency Scores: How to Bootstrap in Nonparametric Frontier Models
AU  - Simar, Léopold
AU  - Wilson, Paul W.
Y1  - 1998/01/01
PY  - 1998
DA  - 1998/01/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/mnsc.44.1.49
DO  - 10.1287/mnsc.44.1.49
T2  - Management Science
JF  - Management Science
JO  - Management Science
SP  - 49
EP  - 61
VL  - 44
IS  - 1
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - Efficiency scores of production units are generally measured relative to an estimated production frontier. Nonparametric estimators (DEA, FDH, ?) are based on a finite sample of observed production units. The bootstrap is one easy way to analyze the sensitivity of efficiency scores relative to the sampling variations of the estimated frontier. The main point in order to validate the bootstrap is to define a reasonable data-generating process in this complex framework and to propose a reasonable estimator of it. This paper provides a general methodology of bootstrapping in nonparametric frontier models. Some adapted methods are illustrated in analyzing the bootstrap sampling variations of input efficiency measures of electricity plants.
AB  - Efficiency scores of production units are generally measured relative to an estimated production frontier. Nonparametric estimators (DEA, FDH, ?) are based on a finite sample of observed production units. The bootstrap is one easy way to analyze the sensitivity of efficiency scores relative to the sampling variations of the estimated frontier. The main point in order to validate the bootstrap is to define a reasonable data-generating process in this complex framework and to propose a reasonable estimator of it. This paper provides a general methodology of bootstrapping in nonparametric frontier models. Some adapted methods are illustrated in analyzing the bootstrap sampling variations of input efficiency measures of electricity plants.
