TY  - JOUR
T1  - Assembly System Design: A Branch and Cut Approach
AU  - Pinnoi, Anulark
AU  - Wilhelm, Wilbert E.
Y1  - 1998/01/01
PY  - 1998
DA  - 1998/01/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/mnsc.44.1.103
DO  - 10.1287/mnsc.44.1.103
T2  - Management Science
JF  - Management Science
JO  - Management Science
SP  - 103
EP  - 118
VL  - 44
IS  - 1
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - This paper addresses the single-product assembly system design problem (ASDP), which seeks to minimize total cost by optimally integrating design (selecting the machine type to locate at each activated station) and operating issues (assigning tasks to observe precedence relationships and cycle time restrictions). We propose an effective branch-and-cut approach for solving single-product ASDPs, adapting inequalities known to be valid for embedded line balancing structures to form inequalities that are valid for the ASDP. The implementation also involves a specialized preprocessor, a heuristic, separation procedures, and an enumeration scheme. Computational tests establish benchmark results for this first implementation of cutting planes for solving the ASDP.
AB  - This paper addresses the single-product assembly system design problem (ASDP), which seeks to minimize total cost by optimally integrating design (selecting the machine type to locate at each activated station) and operating issues (assigning tasks to observe precedence relationships and cycle time restrictions). We propose an effective branch-and-cut approach for solving single-product ASDPs, adapting inequalities known to be valid for embedded line balancing structures to form inequalities that are valid for the ASDP. The implementation also involves a specialized preprocessor, a heuristic, separation procedures, and an enumeration scheme. Computational tests establish benchmark results for this first implementation of cutting planes for solving the ASDP.
